          preview:
            "🌺 I visited Amstelpark especially for the rhododendron valley, and wow—mid-May was the perfect time. It felt like wandering through a botanical rainbow. But…",
          description:
            "🌺 I visited Amstelpark especially for the rhododendron valley, and wow—mid-May was the perfect time. It felt like wandering through a botanical rainbow. But Amstelpark has many surprising corners to offer for photography.\n\n🌿 Amstelpark was originally built for the 1972 Floriade (a nature and garden expo), and you can still feel that vibe in some parts—like the greenhouse tucked away in the corner, or the miniature train making its rounds, there's even a sudden Rietveld House (Durch architect). But what I love is how it’s become a real local park, with layered zones: arboretum, Japanese garden, rose garden, Belgian cloyster garden, open lawns, little sculptures tucked between trees.\n\n📷 Photography tips:\n\n- In the rhododendron valley, try photographing from below the branches—it makes the flowers feel like a canopy.\n-Or try to use differently colored flowers in the fore and background to create interesting color pallettes!\n-Use the winding paths to create depth in your shots.\n-This park invites slowness. Sit for a bit and let your eye wander before your camera does.\n\n👃🏻 And like always, don’t forget your other senses. The rhododendrons don’t just look magical, they smell slightly sweet and earthy. You might even hear city parakeets loudly gossiping overhead.\n\n✅ Visiting tips:\n\n-The rhododendron valley is tucked in the South-West corner of the park near De Borcht. \n-The park is free and open daily.\n-Easy to reach by bike or",
